'''Mazlo''' is a [[jewellery]] house of Lebanese origin, established in [[Paris]] since 1977.<ref>{{cite news|title=L'atelier Mazloum présente ses bijoux contemporains|newspaper=La Revue du Liban|date=March 1974|language=French}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=" Craze in Beirut ", Fresk look at jewelry in enamel|newspaper=The Daily Star|date=September 1969}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=" Une griffe libanaise dans la bijouterie internationale ", Des créations originales signées Mazlo |newspaper=L'Orient - Le Jour|date=August 1981|language=French}}</ref>
Its origins date back to the fifteenth century, when the founder of the dynasty, Georgius Sayegh el-Mazloum left [[Lebanon]] to settle in [[Venice]].<ref>{{cite news|title= Zeitloser Schmuck von Mazlo |newspaper=Goldschmiede Zeitung|date=April 1980|language=German}}</ref>
Since the early-1970s, the house is based in [[Paris]] and headed by Robert Mazloum said "Mazlo." [[Goldsmith]] and [[jeweler]], he revives the family's traditions by creating one off bespoke jewellery pieces.<ref>{{cite news |title= Les bijoux Mazlo assument fleurs, fruits et personnages dans une seule poétique |newspaper=RFBH|date=September 1978|language=French}}</ref>
Parallel to his Haute Joaillerie pieces, he develops a line of prayer beads called "Masbahas" for the Gulf countries, distributed in Tanagra concept stores.<ref>{{cite news|title=" Robert Mazlo", Let them learn to love earth|newspaper=Adam&eve|date=April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=" Mazlo Masbaha", Genuine creativity|newspaper=Ghost|date=August 2011}}</ref>
