{{use dmy dates|date=January 2017}} {{Use New Zealand English|date=January 2017}} {{Infobox sportsperson | name = Peter Aitchison | image = | caption = | birth_name = Peter David Aitchison | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | height = | weight = | sport = [[Rowing (sport)|Rowing]] | club = Union Boat Club, [[Whanganui]] | spouse = Sylvia Dawn Aitchison }} '''Peter David Aitchison''' is a former New Zealand [[Rowing (sport)|rower]] and manufacturer of farming equipment.
A member of the Union Boat Club in [[Whanganui]], Aitchison was a member of the victorious Union crew—along with [[Donald Gemmell]], [[Frank Crotty]], [[Graeme Moran]] and [[Richard Tuffin]] ([[Coxswain (rowing)|coxswain]])—that won the coxed fours title at the New Zealand national rowing championships in 1958. The same crew went on to represent New Zealand at the [[New Zealand at the 1958 British Empire and Commonwealth Games|1958 British Empire and Commonwealth Games]] in Cardiff, finishing fourth.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://unionboatclub.co.nz/2017/01/08/passing-of-frank-crotty/ | title=Passing of Frank Crotty | date=8 January 2017 | publisher=Union Boat Club Whanganui | accessdate=14 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.taradalerotary.co.nz/paul_harris_rotary_awards.htm | title=Paul Harris Fellows | publisher=Rotary Club of Taradale | accessdate=14 January 2017 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170406061006/http://taradalerotary.co.nz/paul_harris_rotary_awards.htm | archivedate=6 April 2017 | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.olympic.org.nz/athletes/peter-aitchison/ |title=Peter Aitchison |year=2016 |website= |publisher=New Zealand Olympic Committee |accessdate=14 January 2017}}</ref>
Aitchison went on to have a successful career as a manufacturer, importer and exporter of farming equipment, founding Aitchison Industries based in Whanganui. The company produces and exports [[seed drill]]s, [[cultivator]]s, fertiliser spreaders and other farming equipment around the world.<ref>{{cite news | title=River City flush with business prosperity | date=19 November 1996 | work=The Dominion | page=9 | first=Jon |last=Morgan}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.reesegroup.co.nz/Aitchison/about.html |title=About Aitchison |year=2009 |website= |publisher=Reese Group |accessdate=14 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Soil conservation equipment ready | date=March 1998 | work=Southerner | page=9 | first=Lyn | last=McKinnon}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Drill 'marriage' opens up new seed methods | date=12 October 1994 | work=New Zealand Farmer | page=28}}</ref>
In 2001, Aitchison and his wife, Sylvia, retired to the [[Wellington]] suburb of [[Roseneath, Wellington|Roseneath]]. In 2015, the couple made national headlines after their neighbour built a four-metre high fence blocking their view of Wellington harbour. After a legal battle, the [[Environment Court of New Zealand|Environment Court]] ordered the fence be removed in January 2016.<ref>{{cite news | title=Fence decision brings relief but no celebrations | date=2 October 2015 | work=Dominion Post | page=3 | first1=Joel | last1=Maxwell | first2=Tom | last2=Hunt}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/life-style/home-property/76143162/environment-court-judge-rules-on-objectionable-wellington-viewblocking-fence | title=Environment Court judge rules on 'objectionable' Wellington view-blocking fence | date=22 January 2016 | work=Stuff.co.nz | accessdate=14 January 2017 | first=David | last=White}}</ref>
