'''Salomón Lerner Ghitis''', also known as '''Siomi Lerner''' (born 4 February 1946)<ref name="Comercio">{{Citation |url=http://elcomercio.pe/politica/918468/noticia-quien-salomon-lerner-ghitis-primer-ministro-ollanta-humala|title=¿Quién es Siomi Lerner, el primer ministro de Ollanta Humala?|newspaper=El Comercio|date=21 July 2011 |language=Spanish|trans-title=Who is Siomi Lerner, Ollanta Humala's prime minister}}</ref> is a [[Peru]]vian businessman and politician, who was [[Prime Minister of Peru]] from 28 July to 10 December 2011 and leader of the political movement Citizens for Change (CxC). He was appointed prime minister following the [[Peruvian general election, 2011|2011 presidential election]] won by [[Ollanta Humala]].<ref>{{Citation|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424053111904233404576460420620240838?mod=googlenews_wsj|title=Peru Leader Taps Moderate Cabinet|first1=Matt|last1=Moffett|first2=Robert|last2=Kozak|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=22 July 2011|accessdate=4 Aug 2011}}</ref> Lerner resigned on 10 December 2011.<ref name=bbc11dec>{{cite news|title=Peru PM Salomon Lerner in surprise resignation|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-16128738|accessdate=13 April 2013|newspaper=BBC|date=10 December 2011}}</ref>

==Early life==
Salomón Lerner is of [[Jews|Jewish]] descent.<ref name=Buckman2012/> He was born on 4 February 1946.<ref name=Comercio/> He studied in [[Colegio San Andrés|Anglo-Peruvian School]]. From 1962 to 1967, he studied industrial engineering with focus on agribusiness at the [[National University of Engineering]] (UNI) in Lima. Later he attended post-gradual courses at the [[Monterrey Institute of Technology and Higher Education|Monterrey Institute of Technology]] in Mexico, in 1968, and at the [[Technion – Israel Institute of Technology|Technion Institute]] in Haifa, Israel, in 1989. As a student, he joined politics and became the chairman of the students' wing of the social-democratic [[American Popular Revolutionary Alliance|APRA]] party.<ref name="Comercio"/>

==Career==
Under the left-wing military administration of [[Juan Velasco Alvarado]] (1968–75), he was general manager of the Public Fish-Meal and Oil Marketing Enterprise (EPCHAP). In the government of Velasco's successor, [[Francisco Morales Bermúdez]], Lerner was vice minister of foreign trade. In 1997, he managed [[CPN Radio]] channel, and from October 1997 to March 1998, he was a member of the board of [[Frecuencia Latina]]. At the end of the 1990s, he served as the CEO of the Banco del Progreso. When the NBK bank acquired Banco del Progreso in 2000, he stayed CEO of the merged bank, until his resignation during the crisis in July of that year.

Other functions performed by Salomón Lerner include manager of Helicópteros del Sur, Tecal S.A., and the Cotton Corporation of Peru, president of the Institute for Economic and Social Development (Indes), and the industrial engineers' chapter in the Association of Peruvian Engineers (CIP).<ref name="Comercio"/>

==Politics==
In 2001, Lerner was general coordinator of the ''Civil Association Transparencia'' which observed the [[Peruvian general election, 2001|2001 general elections]]. Afterwards he became a member of the editorial board of the daily newspaper ''[[La República]]''.<ref name="Comercio"/> He also managed the campaign of left-wing nationalist [[Ollanta Humala]] for both the [[Peruvian general election, 2006|2006]] and the [[Peruvian general election, 2011|2011 presidential election]].<ref name=andina21june>{{cite news|title=Peru's president names prime minister, finance minister|url=http://www.andina.com.pe/english/noticia-perus-president-names-prime-minister-finance-minister-370048.aspx|accessdate=13 April 2013|newspaper=Andina|date=21 June 2011|location=Lima|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130705182422/http://www.andina.com.pe/english/noticia-perus-president-names-prime-minister-finance-minister-370048.aspx|archivedate=5 July 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

===Prime Minister===
On 28 July 2011, [[Peruvian general election, 2011|newly elected]] president Ollanta Humala appointed Salomón Lerner to be President of the Council of Ministers of Peru.<ref name=cosmo13dec>{{cite news|title=Peru’s new cabinet|url=http://www.cosmopolis.ch/english/politics/e0013700/peru_new_cabinet_e01370000.htm|accessdate=13 April 2013|newspaper=Cosmopolis|date=13 December 2011}}</ref> His government had congressional support of the [[Peru Wins]] and [[Possible Peru]] parliamentary groups.<ref name="Comercio"/> During his tenure, the [[government of Peru]] was marked by internal and external debate over the political orientation of the cabinet and Lerner's ability to control, the suspension of the President's 2nd Vice President and some members of Congress,{{Citation needed|date=December 2011}} coupled with social mobilisations and heavy protests, including a dispute over the $4.8 billion Conga gold mining investment project by a Canadian company.{{which|date=December 2011}} On 10 December, he resigned as Prime Minister, without directly referencing to the mining conflict and was succeeded by his Interior Minister [[Oscar Valdés]].<ref name=bbc11dec/><ref name=Buckman2012>{{cite book|author=Robert T. Buckman|title=Latin America 2012|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kMETlYnQINsC&pg=PA341|accessdate=13 April 2013|date=9 August 2012|publisher=Stryker Post|isbn=978-1-61048-888-4|pages=341}}</ref>

