{{advert|date=September 2012}} {{Infobox book | name = The Complete TurtleTrader: How 23 Novice Investors Became Overnight Millionaires | orig title = | translator = | image = The Complete TurlteTrader.jpg | caption = | author = [[Michael Covel]] | cover_artist = | country = | language = | series = | subject = | genre = Business, Non-fiction | publisher = [[HarperCollins Publishers]] (USA) | release_date = 2009 (USA) | media_type = Print | pages = 288 | isbn = 0061241717 | preceded_by = [[Trend Following: Learn to Make Millions in Up or Down Markets]] | followed_by = Trend Commandments: Trading for Exceptional Returns }}
'''''The Complete TurtleTrader: How 23 Novice Investors Became Overnight Millionaires''''' (2009) is an [[international bestseller]] written by [[Michael Covel]].<ref name=bloomberg>Pressley, James. [https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=ab8tmB7aIGQE&refer=home Richard Dennis, Prince of Chicago Pit, Taught Turtles to Trade]. ''Bloomberg''. November 1, 2007.</ref><ref>Rudawsky, Gil. [http://www.dailyfinance.com/2010/05/14/mystery-trader-in-stock-market-crash-outed-yet-questions-remain/ Mystery Trader in Stock Market Crash Outed, Yet Questions Remain]. ''Daily Finance''. May 14, 2010.</ref><ref name=hedgefonder>[http://hedgefonder.nu/2011/09/michael-covel-trend-followings-ambassador/ Michael Covel: Trend Following Ambassador] ''Hedge Fonder''. January 9, 2011.</ref> Covel recounts the story of Wall Street’s [[Richard Dennis]] and his disciples, the Turtles.<ref name=thesimpledollarturtletrader>[http://www.thesimpledollar.com/2011/09/11/review-the-complete-turtletrader/ Review: The Complete Turtle Trader] “The Simple Dollar”.</ref>
==Background== In 1994, Covel picked up an issue of ''[[Financial World]]'' and skimmed through an article titled "Wall Street's Top Players."<ref name=thecompleteturtletrader>{{cite book |title=The Complete TurtleTrader: How 23 Novice Investors Became Overnight Millionaires |last=Covel |first=Michael W. |authorlink= |year=2009 |publisher=HarperBusiness |location= |isbn=0061241717 |page= |pages=288 |url=https://www.amazon.com/The-Complete-TurtleTrader-Investors-Millionaires/dp/0061241717/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1344465762&sr=8-1&keywords=the+complete+turtletrader}}</ref> Amongst famous investors like [[George Soros]] and [[Julian Robertson]], Covel noticed a name he did not recognize at 25th on the list: R. Jerry Parker, who stated that he was trained as a "Turtle" by [[Richard Dennis]] (another name Covel did not recognize).<ref name=thecompleteturtletrader/> Parker was the only investor in the top hundred advertised as being "trained," and as an investor himself, Covel found this story intriguing.<ref name=thecompleteturtletrader/>
==Synopsis== Richard Dennis made over $200 million as a trader.<ref name=futures>Pardo, Robert. [http://www.futuresmag.com/2007/11/15/the-complete-turtletrader-the-legend-the-lessons-t The Complete TurtleTrader: The Legend, the Lessons, the Results]. ''Futures Magazine''. November 15, 2007.</ref> After having a debate with his partner, William Eckhardt, about whether trading is learnable or an inborn talent, they proposed an experiment where they would spend two weeks training novices in the science of trading and then give them each $1 million to invest.<ref name=thecompleteturtletrader/> The inspiration came from a trip Dennis took to a turtle-breeding farm in Singapore, stating, "We are going to grow traders just like they grow turtles."<ref name="Reprint from the Wall Street Journal"> [http://turtletrader.com/images/wsj_turtle_article.pdf Reprint from the Wall Street Journal] ''Turtle Trader''.</ref>
Although each of the 1,000 applicants went through a rigorous application process designed to test their intelligence, ability to manage risk and mathematical skills, the makeup of the chosen Turtles differed greatly; they included a Czechoslovakian-born [[blackjack]] master, a [[Dungeons and Dragons]] game designer, an [[evangelical]] accountant, a [[Harvard Business School|Harvard MBA]], a [[U.S. Air Force]] pilot and a former pianist.<ref name=bloomberg/> The Turtles would go on to gross over $150 million in four years.<ref name=goldseek>Nystrom, Michael. [http://news.goldseek.com/bullnotbull/1206252300.php Book Review] ''GoldSeek''. March 23, 2008.</ref><ref name=mindconnectionreview>Lamendola, Mark.[http://www.mindconnection.com/books/completeturtletrader.htm The Complete TurtleTrader] ''Mindconnection''.</ref>
==Release and reception== ''The Complete TurtleTrader'' was Covel’s second bestseller and ''[[Futures (magazine)|Stocks, Futures, Options Magazine]]'' named ''The Complete TurtleTrader'' as one of 2007’s top 10 trading, investing and personal finance books.<ref name=michaelcovel>[http://www.michaelcovel.com/2007/12/06/top-10-books-of-2007 Top 10 Books of 2007] ''Michael Covel''.</ref> ''[[Bloomberg Businessweek|Bloomberg]]'' noted that the book was worthy of a spot on any investor’s shelf and ''[[The Hindu]]'' called ''The Complete TurtleTrader'' “exciting and educative.”<ref name=bloomberg/><ref name=hindureview>Murali, D. [http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/holnus/002200804051231.htm Make the Right Call] ''The Hindu''. April 5, 2008.</ref><ref>Power, Ben. [http://trendfollowing.com/whitepaper/turtle-article.pdf Michael Covel]. ''Your Trading Edge Magazine''. December 2009.</ref><ref name=forbes>[http://www.turtletrader.com/forbes-review.html Turtle Trader] ''Forbes''.</ref>
